    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://blogcurator.blogspot.com/" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">dervla</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2014/01/in-it-together/#comment-40990"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-01-16T16:25:42-05:00">Thursday, January 16, 2014 at 4:25 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I love this Molly! Don&#39;t worry, i know it&#39;s only your experience you&#39;re drawing from. I too found that exposing my girls to a variety of textures and flavors (and spice levels) at an early age was helpful for overall food curiosity. I allowed them to lead me into the solid food world. When they started grabbing food from my plate then i started introducing morsels of food. I&#39;ve never chopped anything up too tiny, and let them suck on giant hunks of fruit that make other parents nervous &#8230; it works for us 🙂 June is lucky to have you making all that wonderful food for her.</p>
    </div>

