    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Molly, while I don&#39;t have a kid, I hope to one day, and in the mean time, I think this post articulates very well a good approach to eating no matter how squeezable one&#39;s thighs or toussable one&#39;s hair. I hope it&#39;s not too heavy to say here, but I spent a large part of my college years struggling with an eating disorder and it has sharpened my ears to all the anxieties about &#8220;bad food&#8221; that is unfortunately so common. When I have a child, I want to impart the same attitude about food, as sustenance and pleasure and connection, as you so perfectly said. Thanks!</p>
    </div>

