  <li id="comment-41097" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://forcedbloom.wordpress.com/" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">LA Friday</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2014/01/in-it-together/#comment-41097"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-01-29T18:43:56-05:00">Wednesday, January 29, 2014 at 6:43 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Molly, this post is brilliant. If every parent ascribed to your views on feeding a child, food issues would disappear. When my daughter was growing up, we had one rule: you had to taste the food. If she didn&#39;t like a food, I prepared something else. As a kid, I was held hostage at the dinner table until I cleaned my plate&#8211;or sent to bed without supper. I did not like milk, but my mother fretted over it and found ways to get it into me. Turned out I was very sensitive to milk. Our bodies (even very little ones) know what they need, want, and desire.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
